
                           Welcome to Algae
                           ----------------

Copyright (C) 1994-2002  K. Scott Hunziker.
Copyright (C) 1990-1994  The Boeing Company.

See the file COPYING for license, warranty, and permission details.

Algae is an interpreted language for numerical analysis.  Algae was
developed because we needed a fast and versatile tool, capable of
handling large problems.  Algae has been applied to interesting
dynamics problems in aerospace and related fields for more than a
decade.

Algae was designed and implemented by Scott Hunziker and Mike Brennan.

The file "doc/algae.ps" is the Algae User's Manual in postscript form.
A list of known bugs is given in the "Bugs" section of the manual.
Read the file "INSTALL" for installation instructions.  The file
"NEWS" describes significant changes made between versions.  The
"examples" directory contains some warped examples -- look at the
files in the "tools" directory for more typical Algae code.

The Algae source is available at ftp://algae.sourceforge.net/pub/algae
and at ftp://ftp.eskimo.com/u/k/ksh/algae.  The Algae Home Page is on
the WWW at "http://algae.sourceforge.net/index.html".

Please send all comments and bug reports by electronic mail to:

        K. Scott Hunziker <ksh@users.sourceforge.net>

# 3/27/2026 #

Configure for a modern gfortran system on Ubuntu using:

F77=gfortran FFLAGS="-g -O2 -fallow-argument-mismatch" LIBS="-lgfortran -lm" CFLAGS="-g -O2 -std=gnu89" ./configure


Implemented Chapter 8 Projects (April 2026)
-------------------------------------------

The following 8 projects from Chapter 8 ("Projects") in doc/algae.ps
have been implemented in this tree, from easiest to most difficult:

1) Complete fread/fwrite and add fseek/ftell
         - Added missing binary read/write cases in fread/fwrite
                 (including long, float/double, endian and ieee qualifiers).
         - Added fseek(file; offset; whence) and ftell(file).

2) printf/fprintf/sprintf with array arguments
         - Vector and matrix arguments are expanded and consumed by
                 scalar format specifiers.

3) More robust complex atan/atanh
         - Replaced naive formulas with numerically robust algorithms.

4) Readline tab completion
         - Symbol completion now includes variables, user functions,
                 and builtins.

5) Better help system
         - New builtin help() and help("name") for builtin documentation.
         - New docstring(fn; "text") for user-defined function docs.

6) Builtin interface documentation and API header
         - Added doc/BUILTIN_INTERFACE.md for developers.
         - Added src/algae_api.h as a convenience API include.

7) Symbolic debugger
         - Added breakpoints and single-step controls:
                 breakpoint, dbclear, dbstep, dbcont, dbstack, dbstatus.

8) GTK+ interface
         - Added src/gtk_gui.c and build target algae-gtk.


Quick Usage
-----------

Build command-line interpreter:

        make -C src algae

Build GTK interface:

        make -C src algae-gtk

Run Algae normally:

        ./src/algae

Run without startup files (clean environment):

        ./src/algae -S


Feature Usage Examples (Algae code)
-----------------------------------

Binary I/O + file position:

        fwrite("/tmp/data.bin"; [1.0, 2.0, 3.0]);
        close("/tmp/data.bin");
        x = fread("/tmp/data.bin"; 3);
        fseek("/tmp/data.bin"; 8; "set");
        y = fread("/tmp/data.bin"; 1);
        p = ftell("/tmp/data.bin");
        close("/tmp/data.bin");

printf with arrays:

        v = [10, 20, 30];
        s = sprintf("%g %g %g"; v);
        printf("%g %g %g\n"; v);

Help and docstrings:

        help();
        help("sin");

        f = function(x) { return x * x; };
        docstring(f; "Square of x");

Debugger:

        breakpoint("my_script.A"; 42);
        dbstatus();
        dbstep();
        dbcont();
        dbclear();

GTK frontend:

        ./src/algae-gtk


Notes
-----

- The startup tools now keep introductory text in variable help_text,
        so the builtin help() function remains callable.
- For developers adding new C builtins, see doc/BUILTIN_INTERFACE.md.

